(This passage refers to the Christian prosecution by the Soviet communists)

THREAD ON SAINT LUKE OF CRIMEA:

During the times of communism, from ear to ear there was spreading a rumor - a rumor about the Surgeon-Archbishop.

He put the ill on the operating table, read a prayer over them, made the sign of the cross, and then reached for the scalpel.
Bro do you realize that Eugene Sandow was also jewish lmao

In the yellowed photos from those times, an old bearded man wearing a cassock (the black clothing of priests) with long gray hair can be seen. This man was both an Archbishop and a Soviet medical professor.

He spent 40 years in the Russian Soviet regime.
On his books, generations of Soviet medics were taught. He preached and gave sermons, and together with that read lectures and gave dissertations on international Soviet scientific conventions.

The people were amazed at the sight of a surgeon wearing a black priestly garment. The bolshevik propaganda had to fight the obvious:

That the Faith and science are able to coexist.

"How can you believe in the God? Have you seen Him?"

- Asked Peters, a high-rank KGB agent

"No, I have not seen Him. I do a lot of brain surgeries, mister. And when I open the skull - I do not see the mind or the conscience. Do they also not exist?"

- Responded St. Luke.

He was sent to a gulag in the maddening depts of frozen Sibir. There, he saved countless lives and souls by helping the local medics. At times, he had to perform surgeries with kitchen knives, with women's hair instead of surgical string.

There, he was also tortured, threatened, left without food, water or sleep, left in the cold. He was promised to be allowed to return as a honorable medical professor to the capital - only if he disavowed his faith in Christ. He suffered many great tortures, but refused to do it.

He was losing his sight, his feet were swollen, he had Gout, other illnesses... nothing stopped him from doing his service to the suffering and praying to the Lord.

"I believe my primary mission is everywhere and always to pronounce the name of Christ!" - said St. Luke.

When the great Saint died, the Soviets did not want anyone to attend his burial and banned people from going to it.

The faithful disregarded this rule. The funeral procession was 3 kilometers long, with the streets so crowded that nothing could be done to stop it.

Hundreds of ill people who visited his grave those days (and even today) reported being miraculously healed from deathly incurable illnesses. The miracles never stopped, and today the man finds his place among the pantheon of saints.

Here's a short excerpt from a sermon of his:

A man of great mind, who spent his life in hellish tortures but still saved thousands of bodies and souls.

Currently, this man is praying for you and your salvation from Heaven.

Pray to Saint Luke of Crimea, as he prays to God for you, and remember the story of this holy man.

Interesting to note: the few people who know how bad it truly is, me, Logo, BAP, a few others I won't name - people who have researched the rabbit holes and seen some VERY bad stuff - all of us are optimistic and love life.

In contrast, the most vocally "blackpilled" ones tend to be those who have no actual idea about the world's current state of affairs, nor have seen any of the really bad stuff. They've seen a few /pol/ graphs and think they penetrated some secret knowledge. It's far, far worse.

And yet, once you grasp the full reality, you realize that good is always meant to win. Oil always leaves water. A saint's soul always goes to Heaven. The storm rages on, and will rage for the entire day - but the horizon, far away from us, is clear. Keep your chin up, buddy!
